trans-unit.source: This document details how to enable device writeback using Azure AD Connect
trans-unit.target: This document details how to enable device writeback using Azure AD Connect

trans-unit.source: Enabling device writeback in Azure AD Connect
trans-unit.target: Enabling device writeback in Azure AD Connect

trans-unit.source: The following documentation provides information on how to enable the device writeback feature in Azure AD Connect.
trans-unit.target: The following documentation provides information on how to enable the device writeback feature in Azure AD Connect.

trans-unit.source: Device Writeback is used in the following scenarios:
trans-unit.target: Device Writeback is used in the following scenarios:

trans-unit.source: Enable conditional access based on devices to ADFS (2012 R2 or higher) protected applications (relying party trusts).
trans-unit.target: Enable conditional access based on devices to ADFS (2012 R2 or higher) protected applications (relying party trusts).

trans-unit.source: This provides additional security and assurance that access to applications is granted only to trusted devices.
trans-unit.target: This provides additional security and assurance that access to applications is granted only to trusted devices.

trans-unit.source: For more information on conditional access, see [Managing Risk with Conditional Access](active-directory-conditional-access.md) and [Setting up On-premises Conditional Access using Azure Active Directory Device Registration](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn788908.aspx).
trans-unit.target: For more information on conditional access, see [Managing Risk with Conditional Access](active-directory-conditional-access.md) and [Setting up On-premises Conditional Access using Azure Active Directory Device Registration](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn788908.aspx).

trans-unit.source: [AZURE.NOTE] A subscription to Azure AD Premium is required for device writeback.
trans-unit.target: [AZURE.NOTE] A subscription to Azure AD Premium is required for device writeback.

trans-unit.source: Part 1: Install Azure AD Connect
trans-unit.target: Part 1: Install Azure AD Connect

trans-unit.source: Install Azure AD Connect using Custom or Express settings.
trans-unit.target: Install Azure AD Connect using Custom or Express settings.

trans-unit.source: The recommendation is to start with having all users and groups successfully synchronized before you enable device writeback.
trans-unit.target: The recommendation is to start with having all users and groups successfully synchronized before you enable device writeback.

trans-unit.source: Part 2: Prepare Active Directory
trans-unit.target: Part 2: Prepare Active Directory

trans-unit.source: Use the following steps to prepare for using device writeback.
trans-unit.target: Use the following steps to prepare for using device writeback.

trans-unit.source: From the machine where Azure AD Connect is installed, launch PowerShell in elevated mode.
trans-unit.target: From the machine where Azure AD Connect is installed, launch PowerShell in elevated mode.

trans-unit.source: If the Active Directory PowerShell module is NOT installed.
trans-unit.target: If the Active Directory PowerShell module is NOT installed.

trans-unit.source: Install it using the following command:
trans-unit.target: Install it using the following command:

trans-unit.source: With enterprise admin credentials, run the following commands and then exit PowerShell.
trans-unit.target: With enterprise admin credentials, run the following commands and then exit PowerShell.

trans-unit.source: Powershell
trans-unit.target: Powershell

trans-unit.source: Description:
trans-unit.target: Description:

trans-unit.source: If not existent, it creates and configures new containers and objects under CN=Device Registration Configuration,CN=Services,CN=Configuration,[forest-dn].
trans-unit.target: If not existent, it creates and configures new containers and objects under CN=Device Registration Configuration,CN=Services,CN=Configuration,[forest-dn].

trans-unit.source: If not existent, it creates and configures new containers and objects under CN=RegisteredDevices,[domain-dn].
trans-unit.target: If not existent, it creates and configures new containers and objects under CN=RegisteredDevices,[domain-dn].

trans-unit.source: Device objects will be created in this container.
trans-unit.target: Device objects will be created in this container.

trans-unit.source: Sets necessary permissions on the Azure AD Connector account, to manage devices on your Active Directory.
trans-unit.target: Sets necessary permissions on the Azure AD Connector account, to manage devices on your Active Directory.

trans-unit.source: Only needs to run on one forest, even if Azure AD Connect is being installed on multiple forests.
trans-unit.target: Only needs to run on one forest, even if Azure AD Connect is being installed on multiple forests.

trans-unit.source: Parameters:
trans-unit.target: Parameters:

trans-unit.source: DomainName: Active Directory Domain where device objects will be created.
trans-unit.target: DomainName: Active Directory Domain where device objects will be created.

trans-unit.source: Note: All devices for a given Active Directory forest will be created in a single domain.
trans-unit.target: Note: All devices for a given Active Directory forest will be created in a single domain.

trans-unit.source: AdConnectorAccount: Active Directory account that will be used by Azure AD Connect to manage objects in the directory.
trans-unit.target: AdConnectorAccount: Active Directory account that will be used by Azure AD Connect to manage objects in the directory.

trans-unit.source: This is the account used by Azure AD Connect sync to connect to AD.
trans-unit.target: This is the account used by Azure AD Connect sync to connect to AD.

trans-unit.source: If you installed using express settings, it is the account prefixed with MSOL_.
trans-unit.target: If you installed using express settings, it is the account prefixed with MSOL_.

trans-unit.source: Part 3: Enable device writeback in Azure AD Connect
trans-unit.target: Part 3: Enable device writeback in Azure AD Connect

trans-unit.source: Use the following procedure to enable device writeback in Azure AD Connect.
trans-unit.target: Use the following procedure to enable device writeback in Azure AD Connect.

trans-unit.source: Run the installation wizard again.
trans-unit.target: Run the installation wizard again.

trans-unit.source: Select **customize synchronization options** from the Additional Tasks page and click **Next**.
trans-unit.target: Select **customize synchronization options** from the Additional Tasks page and click **Next**.

trans-unit.source: ![Custom Install](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/devicewriteback2.png)
trans-unit.target: ![Custom Install](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/devicewriteback2.png)

trans-unit.source: In the Optional Features page, device writeback will no longer be grayed out.
trans-unit.target: In the Optional Features page, device writeback will no longer be grayed out.

trans-unit.source: Please note that if the Azure AD Connect prep steps are not completed device writeback will be grayed out in the Optional features page.
trans-unit.target: Please note that if the Azure AD Connect prep steps are not completed device writeback will be grayed out in the Optional features page.

trans-unit.source: Check the box for device writeback and click **next**.
trans-unit.target: Check the box for device writeback and click **next**.

trans-unit.source: If the checkbox is still disabled, see the [troubleshooting section](#the-writeback-checkbox-is-still-disabled).
trans-unit.target: If the checkbox is still disabled, see the [troubleshooting section](#the-writeback-checkbox-is-still-disabled).

trans-unit.source: ![Device Writeback](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/devicewriteback3.png)
trans-unit.target: ![Device Writeback](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/devicewriteback3.png)

trans-unit.source: On the writeback page, you will see the supplied domain as the default Device writeback forest.
trans-unit.target: On the writeback page, you will see the supplied domain as the default Device writeback forest.

trans-unit.source: Troubleshooting
trans-unit.target: Troubleshooting

trans-unit.source: The writeback checkbox is still disabled
trans-unit.target: The writeback checkbox is still disabled

trans-unit.source: If the checkbox for device writeback is not enabled even though you have followed the steps above, the following steps will guide you through what the installation wizard is verifying before the box is enabled.
trans-unit.target: If the checkbox for device writeback is not enabled even though you have followed the steps above, the following steps will guide you through what the installation wizard is verifying before the box is enabled.

trans-unit.source: First things first:
trans-unit.target: First things first:

trans-unit.source: Make sure at least one forest has Windows Server 2012R2.
trans-unit.target: Make sure at least one forest has Windows Server 2012R2.

trans-unit.source: The device object type must be present.
trans-unit.target: The device object type must be present.

trans-unit.source: If the installation wizard is already running, then any changes will not be detected.
trans-unit.target: If the installation wizard is already running, then any changes will not be detected.

trans-unit.source: In this case, complete the installation wizard and run it again.
trans-unit.target: In this case, complete the installation wizard and run it again.

trans-unit.source: Make sure the account you provide in the initialization script is actually the correct user used by the Active Directory Connector.
trans-unit.target: Make sure the account you provide in the initialization script is actually the correct user used by the Active Directory Connector.

trans-unit.source: To verify this, follow these steps:
trans-unit.target: To verify this, follow these steps:

trans-unit.source: From the start menu, open **Synchronization Service**.
trans-unit.target: From the start menu, open **Synchronization Service**.

trans-unit.source: Open the **Connectors** tab.
trans-unit.target: Open the **Connectors** tab.

trans-unit.source: Find the Connector with type Active Directory Domain Services and select it.
trans-unit.target: Find the Connector with type Active Directory Domain Services and select it.

trans-unit.source: Under **Actions**, select **Properties**.
trans-unit.target: Under **Actions**, select **Properties**.

trans-unit.source: Go to **Connect to Active Directory Forest**.
trans-unit.target: Go to **Connect to Active Directory Forest**.

trans-unit.source: Verify that the domain and user name specified on this screen match the account provided to the script.
trans-unit.target: Verify that the domain and user name specified on this screen match the account provided to the script.

trans-unit.source: ![Connector account](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/connectoraccount.png)
trans-unit.target: ![Connector account](./media/active-directory-aadconnect-get-started-custom-device-writeback/connectoraccount.png)

trans-unit.source: Verify configuration in Active Directory:
trans-unit.target: Verify configuration in Active Directory:

trans-unit.source: Verify that the Device Registration Service is located in the location below (CN=DeviceRegistrationService,CN=Device Registration Services,CN=Device Registration Configuration,CN=Services,CN=Configuration) under configuration naming context.
trans-unit.target: Verify that the Device Registration Service is located in the location below (CN=DeviceRegistrationService,CN=Device Registration Services,CN=Device Registration Configuration,CN=Services,CN=Configuration) under configuration naming context.

trans-unit.source: Troubleshoot1
trans-unit.target: Troubleshoot1

trans-unit.source: Verify there is only one configuration object by searching the configuration namespace.
trans-unit.target: Verify there is only one configuration object by searching the configuration namespace.

trans-unit.source: If there is more than one, delete the duplicate.
trans-unit.target: If there is more than one, delete the duplicate.

trans-unit.source: Troubleshoot2
trans-unit.target: Troubleshoot2

trans-unit.source: On the Device Registration Service object, make sure the attribute msDS-DeviceLocation is present and has a value.
trans-unit.target: On the Device Registration Service object, make sure the attribute msDS-DeviceLocation is present and has a value.

trans-unit.source: Lookup this location and make sure it is present with the objectType msDS-DeviceContainer.
trans-unit.target: Lookup this location and make sure it is present with the objectType msDS-DeviceContainer.
